<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,807,1229]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,807,832]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body strongly stellate (R/r=3.5â€“5.0), arms elongate, strap-like to triangular in shape. Interradial arcs acute. Arm rectangular in cross-section. Abactinal plates abutted, ranging ranging from flat to convex, covered with a distinct continuous cover of granules. Marginal plates broadly quadrate in outline forming discrete frame around abactinal-lateral outline of body. Marginal plate surface covered by continuous cover of granules Actinal region small, covered by granules. Papulae present between marginal and actinal plate contact. Furrow spines blunt, relatively few, with variable subambulacral armature.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,807,1229]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1023,1048]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1840" box="[343,426,1025,1048]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Fromia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[343,426,1025,1048]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Fromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nominally includes 16 species (
<bibRefCitation author="Mah, C. &amp; Hansson, H." box="[792,1055,1023,1048]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="2017" refId="ref72624" refString="Mah, C. &amp; Hansson, H. (2011) Fromia Gray, 1840. In: Mah, C. L. (2017). World Asteroidea database. Accessed from: http: // www. marinespecies. org / asteroidea / aphia. php? p = taxdetails &amp; id = 123311 (accessed 12 November 2017)" type="book chapter" year="2011">Mah &amp; Hansson, 2011</bibRefCitation>
), many of which, such as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lamarck" baseAuthorityYear="1816" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Fromia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="milleporella">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Fromia milleporella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are commonly encountered and widely occurring throughout the Indo-Pacific region (
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, A. M. &amp; Rowe, F. W. E." pageId="34" pageNumber="35" refId="ref69107" refString="Clark, A. M. &amp; Rowe, F. W. E. (1971) Monograph of Shallow-water Indo-West Pacific Echinoderms. British Museum (Natural History) Publications 690. British Museum (Natural History), London, ix + 238, 31 pls." type="book" year="1971">Clark and Rowe, 1971</bibRefCitation>
). A total of eight 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1840" box="[501,584,1097,1120]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Fromia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[501,584,1097,1120]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Fromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. are known to occur in the Indian Ocean (see Appendix 1). Although historically placed within the 
<taxonomicName box="[498,675,1132,1157]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophidiasteridae</taxonomicName>
(e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, A. M. &amp; Rowe, F. W. E." box="[746,986,1132,1157]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" refId="ref69107" refString="Clark, A. M. &amp; Rowe, F. W. E. (1971) Monograph of Shallow-water Indo-West Pacific Echinoderms. British Museum (Natural History) Publications 690. British Museum (Natural History), London, ix + 238, 31 pls." type="book" year="1971">Clark &amp; Rowe 1971</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, A. M." box="[1001,1200,1132,1157]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="187 - 366" refId="ref69077" refString="Clark, A. M. (1993) An index of names of recent Asteroidea-Part 2: Valvatida. E chinoderm Studies, 4, 187 - 366." type="journal article" year="1993">A.M. Clark 1993</bibRefCitation>
) molecular data has shown that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1840" box="[285,368,1169,1192]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Fromia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[285,368,1169,1192]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Fromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a member of the 
<taxonomicName authority="(Mah &amp; Foltz 2011)" authorityName="Mah &amp; Foltz" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Mah &amp; Foltz" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[607,1009,1167,1192]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">
Goniasteridae (
<bibRefCitation author="Mah, C. L. &amp; Foltz, D. W." box="[780,1002,1167,1192]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="769 - 788" refId="ref72510" refString="Mah, C. L. &amp; Foltz, D. W. (2011) Molecular Phylogeny of the Valvatacea (Asteroidea, Echinodermata). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 161, 769 - 788. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2010.00659. x" type="journal article" year="2011">Mah &amp; Foltz 2011</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Other recent taxonomic adjustments (such as the synonymy of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H.L.Clark" authorityYear="1921" box="[444,591,1204,1228]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Austrofromia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[444,591,1204,1228]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Austrofromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) are mentioned below with the appropriate species.
</paragraph>
